Below is your **Claude Code Bootstrap Specification (CCBS v1.0)**.

This is intentionally **linear, dependency-ordered, and implementation-constrained** so Claude Code can execute it without reinterpretation.

---

# L-CDEA — CLAUDE CODE BOOTSTRAP SPEC v1.0

## (Deterministic Semantic Execution System)

---

# 0. SYSTEM PURPOSE

Build a **deterministic semantic execution engine** composed of:

* Typed semantic compiler (CDL)
* Discourse memory graph (DiscourseState)
* Minimum-effective-computation scheduler (MECP)
* Discourse policy kernel (DPK)
* Canonicalization system (CAS)
* Graph-based execution runtime

---

# 1. HARD GLOBAL INVARIANTS (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

These apply to ALL modules:

## 1.1 Determinism

Same input + same state → identical output

## 1.2 Layer Isolation

No module may access or mutate internal state of another module directly.

## 1.3 Type Safety

All semantic operations must be typed.

## 1.4 MECP Enforcement

No computation expands unless MECP approves it.

## 1.5 Canonical Consistency

Equivalent structures must normalize to identical forms.

---

# 2. SYSTEM EXECUTION PIPELINE (STRICT ORDER)

This order is FIXED.

```text id="pipeline_1"
INPUT
  ↓
(1) Input Parser
  ↓
(2) Lexical + Type Resolution
  ↓
(3) CDL Compiler
  ↓
(4) Canonicalization (CAS)
  ↓
(5) MECP Scheduler (Pruning / Expansion Control)
  ↓
(6) Graph Execution Engine
  ↓
(7) DiscourseState Update
  ↓
(8) Trace Logger
```

---

# 3. CORE MODULES (IMPLEMENT IN THIS ORDER)

---

# 3.1 TYPES MODULE (FIRST BUILD)

## Purpose

Defines all semantic categories.

## Allowed Types:

```text id="types_1"
Entity
Event
State
Process
Relation
Constraint
Abstraction
```

## Rule:

Every CDL operator MUST define:

```text id="type_sig"
input_types → output_type
```

---

# 3.2 CDL MODULE (SEMANTIC CORE)

## Purpose

Deterministic operator-based meaning system.

## Structure:

```text id="cdl_op"
Operator:
  name
  input_types
  output_type
  transformation_rule
```

## Rule:

* CDL is immutable at runtime
* No probabilistic interpretation allowed here

---

# 3.3 INPUT PARSER

## Purpose

Convert raw text → tokens

## Output:

```text id="parse_out"
Tokens + structural hints
```

No semantic decisions yet.

---

# 3.4 TYPE + SENSE RESOLUTION

## Purpose

Map tokens → typed semantic candidates

## Rule:

* generate candidate meanings (top-k only)
* DO NOT prune yet (MECP happens later)

---

# 3.5 CDL COMPILER

## Purpose

Convert typed meanings → CDL graph

## Output:

```text id="cdl_graph"
Directed acyclic graph of operators
```

---

# 3.6 CANONICALIZATION SYSTEM (CAS)

## Purpose

Normalize equivalent CDL graphs

## Operations:

* reorder invariant operations
* merge equivalent subgraphs
* normalize argument structure
* reduce redundant structures

## Rule:

Must be applied BEFORE MECP.

---

# 3.7 MECP SCHEDULER (CONTROL CORE)

## Purpose

Control computational expansion.

## Core rule:

```text id="mecp_rule"
Expand node N only if:
  Expected_Information_Gain / Cost > threshold
```

## Responsibilities:

* prune interpretation branches
* limit depth expansion
* stop early once sufficient certainty reached

## Constraint:

NEVER modifies semantics or CDL rules.

---

# 3.8 GRAPH EXECUTION ENGINE

## Purpose

Execute CDL graphs deterministically.

## Rules:

* pure execution only
* no interpretation logic
* no access to raw text

---

# 3.9 DISCOURSESTATE MODULE (MEMORY)

## Structure:

```text id="disc_state"
nodes:
  Entity | Event | State | Process | Relation

edges:
  typed relations

salience:
  float weights

temporal_index:
  ordered history
```

## Rules:

* only stores canonical outputs
* low-salience decay applied
* updated ONLY after execution

---

# 3.10 DISCOURSE POLICY KERNEL (DPK)

## Purpose

Controls conversational behavior ONLY.

## Allowed:

* explanation ordering
* traversal preferences
* ambiguity presentation style

## Forbidden:

* changing meaning
* modifying CDL graphs
* altering types

---

# 3.11 TRACE LOGGER (REQUIRED)

Every execution MUST produce:

```text id="trace"
input
resolved_types
cdl_graph
canonical_form
mecp_decisions
execution_output
discourse_update
```

---

# 4. SYSTEM CONTROL LAYER RULES

## 4.1 MECP ALWAYS PREVAILS OVER EXPANSION

No branch expansion without MECP approval.

## 4.2 CANONICALIZATION BEFORE PRUNING

Always normalize before MECP evaluation.

## 4.3 DISCOURSE IS POST-EXECUTION ONLY

No pre-execution memory influence allowed.

---

# 5. FAILURE HANDLING RULES

If ambiguity is unresolved:

1. Reduce abstraction level
2. Decompose into simpler CDL primitives
3. Apply MECP fallback selection
4. If still unresolved → request missing context

---

# 6. PERSISTENCE MODEL

## Persistent:

* DiscourseState (canonical only)
* validated CDL outputs

## Transient:

* interpretation branches
* MECP evaluation trees
* intermediate graphs

---

# 7. SYSTEM BOUNDARY RULE

The system is:

> a deterministic semantic execution engine with controlled memory and policy separation

External environment:

* MAY influence DiscourseState only
* MUST NOT affect CDL or type system

---

# 8. IMPLEMENTATION PRIORITY ORDER

Claude Code MUST implement in this order:

1. types/
2. cdl/
3. parser/
4. compiler/
5. canonicalizer/
6. mecp/
7. executor/
8. discourse/
9. dpk/
10. tracing/

---

# 9. MINIMAL VALID SYSTEM (MVP CHECK)

System is valid ONLY if:

* CDL graph executes deterministically
* MECP prunes at least one branch correctly
* DiscourseState updates post-execution
* Canonicalization produces stable outputs
* Trace logs are complete

---

# END OF BOOTSTRAP SPEC v1.0

